  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 연릉(延陵) : '
    value: 계찰(季札)을 말한 것이다. 계찰은 춘추(春秋) 시대 오왕(吳王)  수몽(壽夢)의 작은 아들인데 어진 이름이 있었다. 그리하여 수몽은 계찰을 임금으로 세우려고 하였으나 사양하고 그 형에게 사양하나 받지 아니하였음.
  - key: '[주-D002] 휴양[休浴] : '
    value: 휴식하고 목욕한다는 말이다. 《한서》 곽광전(霍光傳)에, “곽광이 때마침 휴욕하기 위하여 외출하였다[光時休浴出].” 하였다. 요즘 일요일에 같은 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 염매(鹽梅) : '
    value: 소금은 맛이 짜고 매실은 맛이 시니 국물을 만드는 필수품이다. 《서경》 열명(說明)에 “만약 국물을 조미(調味)할 경우에는 네가 염매(鹽梅)의 구실을 하라.” 하였다. 이것은 은고종(殷高宗)이 부열(傅說)을 명하여 정승을 삼을 때의 말이므로 후에 정승이 된 자의 업적을 칭찬하는 말로 쓰고 있다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 동산(東山) : '
    value: 진(晋)나라 사안(謝安)이 처음에 동산(東山)에서 은거하다가 뒤에 조정에 들어와서 벼슬이 재상의 자리에 올랐다. 그래서 세상에서 은거하다 다시 나온 사람을 동산재기(東山再起)라 칭한다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 남양(南陽)의 용 : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 제갈량(諸葛亮)을 말한 것이다. 제갈량이 남양(南陽)의 초당에 은거하였고, 도호(道號)는 와룡(臥龍)이므로 남양룡이라 칭한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 白 : '
    value: 百
english:
  title: Stele Inscription for Minister Han of Sangdang, Prime Minister of the State Council
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: "Since ancient times, when sage-rulers and enlightened monarchs have guided the mandate of heaven to establish their kingdoms, they have always needed heroes and exceptional men of unified purpose and virtue to labor at their sides, to counsel and assist them, and thus to accomplish deeds of unprecedented magnitude. Therefore, when King Xuan of Zhou achieved restoration, Fang Shu and Zhao Hu served as his ministers; when Liu Xiu of Han recovered the empire, Jia Fu and Deng Yu became his counselors. When our Great Ancestor came to the throne, he gathered talents and heroes who followed like shadows, yet it was Minister Han of Sangdang who stood first among those who offered grand strategies to perfect the great work.\n\nThe Minister's name was Ming-hoe, with courtesy name Cha-jun. Of the Han clan, a great family of Cheongju since ancient times, his remote ancestor Nam assisted the founder of Goryeo and received the title of Samhan Meritorious Subject. Through generations, the family maintained its virtue. His ancestor Kang served in the court of King Gojong as director of the Bureau of Court Rituals. Another ancestor, Saggi, became Vice Remonstrator. Ock held the position of Sangdang Puowon-gun three times over. Gongui was a Chancellery Scholar. Soo served as administrator of the Houkdeok palace and was posthumously appointed Left Prime Minister—the Minister's great-grandfather. He had a son Sangchil, who served as Commissioner of the State Council and was posthumously appointed Left Counselor. Sangchil had a son Ki, a censor, who was the Minister's father. By virtue of the Minister's achievements, his father received the posthumous rank of Pure-Hearted and Virtuous Merit Subject, Great Commandant and Stabilizer of State, Senior Grand Commandant of the State Council, and Prime Minister of Sangdang.\n\nThe Minister's mother was Lady Yi of the Yeongheung line, daughter of Yi Jeok, Great Master of the Mun'gwon Academy. He was born in the tenth month of 1425. Born only seven months after conception, his limbs were not fully formed, and the household considered not raising him. But an elderly maidservant placed him in old padding and cared for him diligently. After months passed, he grew stronger. Black marks like star patterns appeared on his back and abdomen, and all who saw them wondered at such signs.\n\nOrphaned early, he fell into destitution but eventually came to depend upon his grand-uncle, Chamberlain Sangdeok, who observed: \"This child's bearing is extraordinary. He shall surely restore our house.\" From youth, the Minister loved reading and pursued the studies required for the civil service examinations. Though he reached manhood and failed the examinations repeatedly, he remained untroubled, saying to those who inquired: \"The rise and fall of gentlemen lies in fate. Why should I grieve like pedants and common men?\" \n\nHe formed a death-friendship with Gwon Nam, enjoying such harmony that not even Guan Zhong and Bao Shuya could compare. Together they wandered mountains and streams, unmindful of time's passage, their hearts indifferent to fame and fortune. The Minister once jested to his friend: \"In literature and virtue, I yield to you. But in affairs of state and governance—could I yield so easily?\" When he spoke, his words were piercing and extraordinary; all recognized him as a man of great capacity.\n\nIn 1452, at age thirty-eight, he received appointment as an attendant to the Gyeongdeok Palace. The king had recently passed, leaving a young successor, while scheming ministers seized power and the realm teetered toward chaos. Troubled by the disorder, the Minister spoke to his friend: \"The times have reached such extremity. An ambitious prince plots with great ministers, gathering followers, promising rebellion. Catastrophe approaches by the hour. Do you not see it?\" His friend replied: \"Your assessment is sound, but with whom shall we make our plan?\" The Minister answered: \"To restore order requires a true sage-king. The First Prince possesses the wisdom of Han Gaozu and the valor of Tang Taizong. Heaven's mandate is clear. You who serve at the prince's side—why not quietly propose this at the right moment?\" \n\nHis friend brought this counsel to the future king, speaking of the Minister's talents and recommending him as \"today's Guan Zhong—second to none among those fit to serve the state.\" The future king summoned him urgently. The Minister came capped and presented himself. Seeing him, the king seized his hand and said: \"Why do we meet so late? Though the young sovereign reigns, with your aid he might well preserve the realm. Yet the great ministers betray him, and scheming powers cloud his council. Where shall I place the spirits of our ancestors who entrusted their young heir to us?\" Tears fell. The Minister responded with passionate eloquence, laying out the strategy of restoration. \"Though circumstances appear desperate,\" he urged, \"Your Highness, as a prince of the blood, moves against rebels in justice. Victory cannot fail. As the ancients say: 'When the time demands decision, hesitation brings only calamity.' I urge you—consider deeply.\" The king replied: \"Speak no more. My resolve is set.\"\n\nThereafter, all secret counsels were entrusted to the Minister's planning. He advised: \"Han Gaozu relied on Zhang Liang and Chen Ping for strategy, yet deployed Han Xin and Peng Yue for battle. Tang Taizong relied on Fang Xuanling and Du Ruhui for governance, yet deployed Li Jing and Yuchi Jingde for war.\" Thus he recommended dozens of capable military commanders. In the tenth month of 1453, when the uprising was launched, certain waverers sought to dissuade the troops. The Minister drew his sword and declared: \"All who live must die—this cannot be changed. To die for the state surpasses a meaningless death. Any who dissent shall be executed.\" With this, he gathered volunteers, overthrew the conspirators, and restored order to the realm. Though born from the king's brilliant strategy and wise resolve, the work of calculation and decision-making fell largely to the Minister.\n\nHe was promoted to Inspector of Military Equipment, then to Vice Director of the Court of Royal Carriages, and received the rank of Meritorious Subject for Loyal Service and Orderly Peace. In 1454, he became Vice Commissioner of the Royal Secretariat. In 1455, when the king ascended the throne, he received the rank of Co-Meritorious Subject for Harmonious Assistance and was promoted to Right Vice Commissioner.\n\nIn 1456, the Minister discerned a plot. Rebels including Lee Jae and Seong Sammun planned to strike during a grand banquet at Gwangyeon Pavilion. The Minister advised: \"The pavilion is cramped. The Crown Prince should not attend, and the sword-bearing guards should remain outside.\" This counsel was accepted. When the conspirators saw their plans thwarted, some sought to kill the Minister. But Seong Sammun said: \"If the great deed fails, what profit in slaying Han? Better to preserve him.\" When the plot was exposed the next day, all rebels were executed. That the Crown Prince did not attend and the guards remained outside—such foresight prevented the conspiracy's success. Though the ancestors' hidden blessings protected the realm, the Minister's loyalty surely moved heaven itself to aid the throne.\n\nThat winter he was promoted to Chief Commissioner. The king said of him: \"Han is my Zhang Liang.\" In 1457, he received exceptional promotion to Senior Grand Commandant, Minister of Personnel, and Prince of Sangdang. That winter, sent to request the investiture of the Crown Prince at the Chinese court, he fulfilled his mission with excellence.\n\nWhen the realm faced famine in three provinces, the Minister was dispatched as Inspector General. With tireless devotion to relief, the people survived. When others proposed administrative reorganizations that the Minister foresaw would cause hardship, he remonstrated: \"Though order requires adjustment, sudden changes trouble the common folk. The frontier outposts you wish to close serve vital functions.\" His counsel prevailed.\n\nSimilarly, when ambitious officials sought to increase military conscription beyond sustainable levels, the Minister argued: \"Quality in arms matters more than quantity.\" His advice prevented the people's ruin.\n\nThroughout his career, whether as Inspector of distant provinces, as military administrator when the northern frontier flared with tribal incursions, or as chief counselor to successive kings, the Minister never wavered in his devotion. When wild tribes threatened the border and the king wished to lead an army in person, the Minister said: \"These minor bandits require no imperial campaign. Though I am no great warrior, I suffice to suppress them.\" He proceeded to the Six Forts, displayed military might, and won the submission of all tribes without battle. The king marveled: \"To subdue without fighting—this is excellence itself.\"\n\nHis wisdom extended to civil matters. When the National Academy lacked books, he proposed building a library. This was approved, and he personally contributed resources to gather tens of thousands of volumes for scholarship.\n\nIn 1463, the Chinese court requested military aid against the Jurchens. When the first expedition failed, all counseled against a second attempt. The Minister alone insisted: \"Our ancestors have always honored the great power with utmost sincerity. To refuse aid now would betray this trust and invite criticism from China. We must send our best general.\" He persuaded the king to dispatch another force, which returned victorious. The king said: \"Your strategy prevailed. You have brought honor to the state.\"\n\nAt age sixty-nine, when the Minister was sent as envoy to the imperial court, all feared for him at such an age. He replied: \"A minister who receives great favor and generous stipend should not hesitate even at death in service. How could I demur at a mission of homage?\" All admired his resolve. The emperor, hearing of his arrival, said: \"The loyal old Han has come again,\" and bestowed rare gifts. When he departed, the emperor sent an escort to the border—unprecedented honor.\n\nThe Minister urged restoration of the Great Wall, the Compilation of the Royal Annals, and when a comet appeared, he warned of heaven's displeasure and urged strengthened palace defenses. During his later years, as honors accumulated, he grew ever more cautious, fearing success itself. He built a pavilion south of the capital, naming it the Gull-Befriending Pavilion, hoping to retire in peace. Yet the king, through repeated edicts praising his virtue and merit, would not permit his withdrawal.\n\nWhen the king fell ill during his final years, the throne sent physicians and daily inquiries. When asked his final words, the Minister replied: \"His Majesty surpasses the hundred kings. What wisdom could this humble servant offer? Only that I regret abandoning the illuminated age.\" When officials came to receive his words, he rose, donned his regalia, and spoke from his deathbed: \"The Sage is supremely wise. Yet as mortals wax and wane in effort, I entreat him: let diligence at the end equal diligence at the start.\" With these words, he passed at age seventy-three.\n\nThe king, grief-stricken, reduced his meals and suspended court. Through envoys he mourned: \"Your merit and virtue outshine all ministers. To me, you were as family. My sorrow knows no end.\" The king granted exceptional funeral honors and ordered all officials to attend the ceremony.\n\nThe Minister's bearing was broad and generous, his thoughts profound and far-reaching. Of striking appearance and commanding presence, in his youth all recognized him as destined for the highest office. Yet he dwelled long in minor posts, content in spirit. When the Great Ancestor discovered him, he became heart and arm of state, orchestrating strategy, subduing rebellion. Rising from common cloth to the highest ranks in mere years, he managed great affairs with ease, attending to fundamentals rather than minutiae. Through three reigns he moved between military and civil office, standing as pillar of the state for over thirty years. In merit, wealth, and happiness, none in ages past could compare.\n\nHe married Lady Min of Yeongheung, daughter of the posthumously-honored Right Prime Minister. They had one son who achieved rank and title, and four daughters—two of whom became queens. The younger wife bore seven sons and six daughters. His descendants prospered.\n\nWhen his burial was arranged, his son requested this inscription. How can this humble scholar refuse? In my youth, I studied under the great Master Ryu alongside this Minister and his friend. We three grew to know each other's hearts. Though I was fortunate to pass the examinations first, these two friends were long delayed in their advancement. When at last they achieved high office and great position, I remained humble and obscure, gaining my station only through their patronage. My friend departed long ago. Of our fellowship in adversity, only he and I remain. The Minister entrusted his later affairs to my care. Now the mountain crumbles and the beam breaks. I have nothing left to which to look. I record the outline of his life's merit and virtue and inscribe this stone. The tears that follow are all I can offer.\n\nThe inscription reads:\n\nHeaven and earth converge their essence,\nThe mountains and rivers yield their breath—\nA talent rare in ten thousand years,\nA vessel fit to govern the realm.\n\nIn days of obscurity he harbored great intent,\nLike Xie An on Eastern Mountain.\nWhen fortune turned, he rose and fell in rhythm,\nLike Zhuge Liang, the Crouching Dragon of Nanyang.\n\nThe Great Ancestor's discovery was rare—\nA meeting ordained by thousand-year fate.\nCalculating with his counting rods of strategy,\nHe brought the great work to completion.\n\nBearing up heaven, threading through the sun,\nHis loyalty shone bright and clear.\nMountain worn to whetstone, river bound as sash,\nHis merit glows through endless time.\n\nDeep as the prime minister's chamber,\nHigh as the Unicorn Pavilion,\nLeading armies or administering state,\nHe stood as pillar of the realm.\n\nIn his single body, safety and peril balanced;\nIn his fate, all fortune rose and fell.\nPast seventy, his blessings knew no bound—\nEqual to Lujun in scope, to Guo Ziyi in duration.\n\nYet heaven claimed him suddenly;\nA mirror's light was darkened.\nThough the man has passed away,\nWhat endures does not decay.\n\nVirtue exerted, merit achieved—\nLoyalty and diligence remain.\nWho shall praise his brilliance?\nHistory's pages shine with his name.\n\nLooking west toward his burial ground,\nThere lies his sacred hall.\nHeaven sends its auspicious signs;\nHis descendants shall flourish and thrive.\n\nIf any doubt the truth of this,\nLet them read what this stone proclaims."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yangling (延陵) refers to Ji Zha of Wu, a virtuous prince of the Spring and Autumn period who refused the throne, remaining true to his principles—referenced here as the highest standard of moral integrity one might choose.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Crouching Dragon of Nanyang' (臥龍) is Zhuge Liang of Han dynasty, who lived in reclusion in Nanyang before emerging to become a founding minister—symbolizing how a hidden sage becomes revealed when opportunity meets virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Yanfu (鹽梅), literally salt and plum, refers to the essential flavoring agents in sauce-making and serves as a metaphor for a great minister who is indispensable to good governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The inscription's comparison to historical figures—Lujun (潞國) being Wen Yanbo and Guo Ziyi representing officials of extraordinary merit and longevity—places Minister Han among the greatest statesmen of Chinese history.
